^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In terms of the bidding, this is one of the most interesting hands we have ever seen in all my teaching sessions. So I will write an extensive explanation of the bidding which you can then integrate into the movie.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


sk|e|md|4S358TQHTD234C347T,S7H36D5679JKAC29K,S2469KH249D8TQC6A,|sv|n|NT||lb|*mWould you open this hand 2C?^Yes~No~It is a close call^2|lb|*bIf you would not open 2C, what should be the bid by East?^^1H|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|1@H is the correct bid. Is East strong enough to open 2@C? It is close, but I do not think so. A fairly easy and effective way to decide whether or not to open 2@C is to use what I call the "9 trick rule". |
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you think your hand will take 9 tricks opposite a partner with no HCP and average distribution, you should open 2@C. East can count 8 tricks for sure -- 7 hearts and a spade. If you wanted to argue that it is possible that East will take a club trick, which would give East a 9th trick, that is plausible but a bit aggressive. I think East's hand is worth about 8.5 tricks, not quite enough to open 2@C.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is also the Marty Bergen "4 and 4" rule for deciding whether or not to open 2@C. That rule says you can open 2@C if you have 4 quick tricks and 4 losers. The quick trick counting part of the rule is straight forward. But the "4 loser" part of the rule is not. So recently I have decided to simplify by combining the Marty Bergen rule with the 9 trick rule. |
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My 9 winners rule is essentially equivalent to 4 losers. So you can open 2@C if you have 9 winners and 4 quick tricks. On this hand, East only has 3 quick tricks (2 in hearts and 1 in spades) so the hand does not qualify.|mb|1H|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


mb|p|sk|W|NT||lb|*bE/W play 2/1. What should be the bid by West?^^2d|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|West should bid 2@D. Although West only has 11 HCP, she has a clear game force. Using Bergen starting Points, her hand is worth 11 HCP + 3 length points + 1 quality suit point for a total of 15. That is more than enough to force to game.|mb|2D|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


mb|p|sk|e|NT||lb|*bWhat should be the bid by East?^^3H|mb|3H|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Bid ^*B3@H^*N - In the 2/1 style, a jump rebid in your suit has a very specific meaning once a game force has been established. It does NOT show the same thing as a jump rebid in a non-game forcing auction (such as 1@H-1N-3@H). In that auction, 3@H shows a medium hand with a nice 6-card suit. |
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But 3@H has a completely different meaning once a game force has been established. The message 3@H conveys is "Partner, I have a self sufficient suit. That suit is going to be our trump suit. Please start control bidding so we can see if we can bid slam."|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What is a "self sufficient" suit? Since voids are extremely rare, you can assume partner has at least a singleton in your suit. A self sufficient suit is a suit where you likely have at most one loser opposite a singleton. East's heart suit clearly qualifies as being self sufficient. In fact, it is likely to have no losers even opposite a void. |
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Even if the opponents hold 6 cards in hearts, the odds that they break no worse than 4-2 is well over 90%, meaning that East is virtually guaranteed that he will have no heart losers no matter how many hearts partner holds.|mb|p|sk|w|NT||lb|*bWest is interested in slam. What should be the bid now?^^3s|mb|3S|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|3@S is the correct bid. West is showing first or second round control in spades, That means West is showing an ace, king, singleton, or void. On this hand, East can make a 3@S control bid because her singleton is second round control.|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


mb|p|sk|E|NT||lb|*mEast wishes to show his diamond void. Is 4D technically a correct bid?^It is~It is not~It is not but the best available^3|mb|4D|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For many reasons 4@D is the best bid available. East knows their side has enough points to be in slam. The only issue is whether or not their side has two quick club losers. The way to find that out is for East to bid 4@D. That conveys 2 messages. It says "Partner, I have first or second round control in diamonds". It also says "Partner, I do not have first or second round control in clubs". Why is that? Because you always make the cheapest control bid you can make. So since East bypassed 4@C, that says he does not have a control in clubs.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Although I would bid 4@D with the East hand, technically that may not be a 100% correct bid. I did say that you can control bid with shortness (singleton or void) as well as with high cards (ace or king). However, you should not control bid with shortness in partner's suit. Since West bid 2@D, theoretically East should only bid 4@D with the @DA or @DK, not with diamond shortness. However, on this hand, East wants to convey his concern about his lack of a club control. And 4@D is the best way to convey that message.|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let me give you anther expert's bid. Rather than 4@D, some experts would bid 3N. That is not a natural bid because East's 3@H bid already set hearts as the trump suit. Rather, it is a space saving bid asking West to make another control bid. |
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That works perfectly on this hand. West will bid 4@C over 3N and East will now know that their side has clubs controlled. In that case, over 4@C, East can simply bid 6@H, knowing that he has first round control in spades, hearts, and diamonds, and at least 2nd round control in clubs. But for now we stay with the current bidding.|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


mb|p|sk|w|NT||lb|*bWhat should West bid now?^^4n|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|4NT - West know that 4@D indicates that East is concerned about a club control. But she has the @CK and therefore has the club control that East was worried about. That means, knowing that her side has controls in all the side suits, East can now bid 4NT just to make sure their side has enough key cards to bid slam.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||mb|4N|mb|p|NT||sk|E|lb|*yOf course you know how to respond to 4N with a void. Should East report the diamond void?^^n|lb|*bOf course not. Then what should be the bid by East--RKC 1430?^^5D|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Bid 5@D.|mb|5D|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is a way to show a void when responding to 4NT. However, you should only show a "useful" void. A  useful void is a void not in partner's suit. Since West bid 2@D, East's diamond void is not  useful, so he should bid 5@D (assuming they are playing 1430 responses) to show 0 or 3 key cards. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Based on the auction, West can be quite sure that East has 3 key cards, not 0. Since East showed a self-sufficient heart suit, he must have at least one heart key card, otherwise he would not have at most 1 heart loser. So he cannot have 0 key cards.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Had the diamond void been useful, then East would have responded 6@D to 4N. A jump to 6 of a suit over 4NT shows a void in that suit and an odd number of key cards (1 or 3).  The only restriction is that East must never bid past 6 of the trump suit. So, if East had a spade void and an odd number of key cards, he would bid 6@H (since 6@S would force their side to 7@H). If East had responded 6@H, then West would know that East had a spade void with 1 or 3 key cards.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If East had a void with an even number of key cards (2 or 4), he would respond 5NT. This does not identify where the void is, but it is the best you can do when you have to show an even number of key cards.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


mb|p|sk|W|lb|*bWhat should be the bid by West?^^6h|cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Missing only 1 key card and knowing East has a self sufficient heart suit, West has an easy 6@H call.|mb|6H|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|sk||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is one additional interesting point on this hand. Once partner bids 4NT, she is the "captain" of the auction and you must abide by whatever decision she makes regarding whether or not your side should be in slam. However, this hand is a very very rare exception to that rule. Let us suppose that West bid 5@H over 5@D. That would mean East/West are missing 2 key cards. (West would bid 6@H if missing only 1 key card.) Since East has 3 key cards, he knows that the 2 key cards their side are missing are the @CA and @DA. However, with his diamond void, they will not be losing a diamond trick. So in this very rare instance, East could and should override a 5@H bid by West and bid 6@H.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But you should virtually never override partner when he is the one who initiates RKCB. This is an extremely rare exception to that rule.|
