^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The bidding was ok, assuming you play the Bergen OBAR style. Let me briefly review it. OBAR stands for "Over Opponents Bid And Raise." Bergen believes you should "pre balance" whenever the auction goes 1x-P-2x, especially if the opponents bid a major. That means if you have something to say you should say it, even with not that many points. |
PG| ***** 80 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Basically you should make the same bid as you would if it went 1@H-P-2@H-P-P. Because then you would be balancing and don't need that good a hand to bid. So if you play OBAR, you pretend you are balancing. Which means if you have a long suit you bid it, or if you have a singleton and 3+ cards in the other suits you can make a takeout double. You can also bid 2N which is takeout for the minors. Not only 5-5. It could be 5-4 or even 4-4 with 2 good minor suits.|
PG| ***** 81 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Usually when you make an OBAR bid you are short in the opps suit, and this was not the case with North hand. Plus the @HK is in a dubious position. He probably could pass. As I said, I only told him to bid so I could discuss OBAR. I think if I had his hand at an actual table I would pass (reluctantly as usual :) :).|
PG| ***** 82 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Kadu on the other hand needs to be aggressive with her hand. She has 11 Dummy Points. I might treat that as a 3-card limit raise. But she has lots of quacks. So she made the (uncharacteristic for her) conservative bid of 2@H, which is reasonable.|
